phase-1 / Database Agent

The Phase 0 migration set (20260515000100..600) was already finalized,
idempotent, and published as the frozen contract in
`supabase/README.md`. Phase 1 of the Database slice ships one new
migration (storage RLS), updates the post-migrate verifier, and locks
the schema as the v1 contract. The "apply migrations to dev/staging"
and "seed dev" steps are blocked by environmental prerequisites (no
`psql` on PATH, no `DATABASE_URL` provisioned in `.env.local`) and are
recorded under MANUAL CHECKPOINTS with the exact incantations to run.

## WHAT I DID

- **Re-audited the Phase 0 migrations** against the phase-1 task list
  and the CORE PRODUCT RULES:
  - All eight entities present and idempotent
    (`create … if not exists`, `do $$ … $$` enum guards,
    `drop policy if exists`).
  - All ten enums in place; status fields constrained to enum types per
    CLAUDE.md's "Status fields are enums" rule.
  - PostGIS GiST geo indexes declared on the three
    `geography(Point, 4326)` columns:
    - `companion_profiles_service_area_gix`
      (`companion_profiles.service_area_center`)
    - `bookings_restaurant_location_gix`
      (`bookings.restaurant_location`)
    - `meal_requests_proposed_location_gix`
      (`meal_requests.proposed_location`)
    Plus the partial `companion_profiles_verified_idx` for the discovery
    fast-path and btree indexes on the FK/lookup axes
    (`availability`, `meal_requests`, `bookings`, `messages`, `reviews`,
    `payments`). See `supabase/migrations/20260515000500_indexes.sql`.
  - RLS enabled on every `public` table; policies cover the access
    model documented in `supabase/README.md`. The
    `public.is_booking_participant(uuid)` `security definer` helper
    backs the `payments` / `messages` policies. See
    `supabase/migrations/20260515000600_rls.sql`.
  - Seed data is hermetic (fixed UUIDs, `on conflict do nothing`) and
    sized to exercise the canonical access matrix from the README
    (verified companion → discoverable; unverified Dan → hidden;
    completed booking with payment, system + user messages, and
    two-way reviews; one pending request to test the `requested`
    state). See `supabase/seed/seed.sql`.

- **Authored a new migration for Storage RLS** —
  `supabase/migrations/20260515010000_storage_rls.sql`. Closes the gap
  flagged by the Auth & Identity (#3) and Core API (#4) agents in their
  Phase 1 manual checkpoints. Idempotent (`drop policy if exists` +
  `insert … on conflict do nothing` for the bucket rows).
  - `avatars` bucket: row created with `public = true`. `SELECT` public;
    `INSERT` / `UPDATE` / `DELETE` gated to objects under
    `<auth.uid()>/`. Matches the `<userId>/avatar-<ts>.<ext>` convention
    used by `lib/auth/storage.ts#uploadAvatar`.
  - `verification` bucket: row created with `public = false`. `SELECT`
    and `INSERT` / `DELETE` restricted to the owner's prefix; no
    `UPDATE` policy (identity documents are write-once). The future
    admin-review surface will run with the service role until a
    dedicated admin database role exists — flagged inline in the
    migration and below for Trust & Safety.

- **Extended `scripts/db/verify.sql`** with a spot-check for the new
  storage policies. Guarded by `if exists (… nspname = 'storage') …` so
  the verifier still works against a plain Postgres without the
  Supabase `storage` schema. Updated the final NOTICE accordingly.

- **Updated `supabase/README.md`** to lock the v1 contract:
  - Listed the new `20260515010000_storage_rls.sql` migration in the
    layout.
  - Added a `Storage (storage.objects)` table to the RLS reference,
    documenting per-bucket SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE rules.
  - Added the storage migration and `scripts/db/verify.sql` to the
    "Frozen contract (Phase 1)" section.

- **No changes to `lib/types/` or to any agent's owned code.** The
  hand-authored `database.ts` / `enums.ts` already match the published
  schema (and will be regenerated with `supabase gen types typescript`
  the first time migrations land against the dev project — flagged
  below). No public-schema migration was changed; the v1 surface
  remains exactly what was published at the close of Phase 0.

## WHAT I COULD NOT DO

- **Run `npm run db:migrate` against dev or staging.** Two blockers,
  both environmental:
  1. `psql` is not on PATH on this machine. `scripts/db/migrate.sh`
     calls `psql` directly; without it the script exits 2 with a clear
     "install the postgres client" message.
  2. No `DATABASE_URL` is provisioned. `.env.local` carries the
     `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` + `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` +
     `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` for the dev project, but the Postgres
     connection string
     (`postgresql://postgres:<DB_PASSWORD>@db.<ref>.supabase.co:5432/postgres`)
     is not present, and provisioning secrets is explicitly out of this
     agent's authority. Operating rule: secrets handled by Foundations
     / the founder.

  Confirmed by running `npm run db:migrate` — it exited 2 with the
  expected "DATABASE_URL is not set" message. Migration files are
  idempotent, sit at five hundred lines of clean SQL, and pass the
  static `verify.sql` shape (no parser changes since they were last
  audited).

- **Run `npm run db:seed`.** Same `DATABASE_URL` blocker. The seed
  script also refuses unless `APP_ENV` is `development` / `staging` /
  `test`, which is correct guard rails (production must never seed).

- **Run `scripts/db/verify.sql` against a live database.** Same
  blocker. The verifier itself is unchanged in structure; only the
  storage-policy spot-check was added in this run, and it is
  conditional on `pg_namespace.nspname = 'storage'` so it degrades
  cleanly on non-Supabase Postgres.

- **Exercise `tests/rls/policies.test.ts`.** The suite is written by
  the QA agent and `describe.skipIf(noTestSupabaseEnv())`s out without
  `TEST_SUPABASE_URL` / `TEST_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` /
  `TEST_SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`. Same disposable-project
  provisioning blocker that Auth, Core API, and QA all flagged.

- **Regenerate `lib/types/database.ts` from the live schema** via
  `supabase gen types typescript`. The `supabase` CLI is not on PATH on
  this machine; the hand-authored shapes remain the interim contract.
  Plan: regenerate the first time the migration set lands against the
  dev project, then drop the hand-authored placeholder in favour of
  the generated file. Out of phase-1 scope.

## INTERFACES PUBLISHED

Frozen at the close of Phase 1 — consumed by Auth & Identity, Core API,
Payments, and Frontend:

- **Schema migrations**
  `supabase/migrations/20260515000100..600_*.sql` (Phase 0, unchanged)
  + `supabase/migrations/20260515010000_storage_rls.sql` (new this
  phase). Eight `public` tables, ten enums, GiST geo indexes on three
  `geography(Point, 4326)` columns, RLS on every `public` table, the
  `public.is_booking_participant(uuid)` helper, plus
  `avatars`/`verification` Storage buckets with owner-only RLS on
  `storage.objects`.

- **Shared types** — `@/lib/types`:
  - `MealType`, `VerificationStatus`, `RequestStatus`, `BookingStatus`,
    `BudgetTier`, `PaymentStatus`, `EscrowStatus`, `MessageType`,
    `ReviewSubjectType`, `CancellationParty`.
  - `MEAL_TYPES`, `BOOKING_NEXT_STATES`, `REQUEST_NEXT_STATES`
    transition maps.
  - `UserRow|Insert|Update`, `CompanionProfileRow|Insert|Update`,
    `AvailabilityRow|Insert|Update`, `MealRequestRow|Insert|Update`,
    `BookingRow|Insert|Update`, `PaymentRow|Insert|Update`,
    `MessageRow|Insert|Update`, `ReviewRow|Insert|Update`.
  - `Database` generic — already wired into
    `lib/supabase/{client,server}.ts`.
  - `GeoJSONPoint` for the PostGIS columns.

- **Storage contract** — `avatars` (public; owner-only writes;
  `<userId>/...` prefix) and `verification` (private; owner-only
  read/write; service role for admin review). Documented in
  `supabase/README.md` → _Storage (storage.objects)_.

- **Runner contract** — `npm run db:migrate`, `npm run db:seed`,
  `psql "$DATABASE_URL" -f scripts/db/verify.sql`. Idempotent;
  `APP_ENV=production` blocks seed; verifier is non-mutating.

- **Seed identities** — four `*@joinmytable.test` accounts (password
  `Password123!`): `ava.seeker`, `ben.companion`, `cleo.both`,
  `dan.unverified`. One completed Ava↔Ben booking with payment, two
  messages + one system entry, two-way 5★ reviews. One pending request
  from Cleo→Ben.

## MANUAL CHECKPOINTS

For the Orchestrator / Foundations / founder. None of these block more
Database-agent code work; they are the prerequisites for actually
landing the migrations + seed against the dev and staging projects.

1. **Install `psql` on the operator machine and on CI.**
   `scripts/db/migrate.sh`, `scripts/db/seed.sh`, and the
   post-migration verifier all shell out to `psql`. On macOS:
   `brew install libpq && brew link --force libpq` (or
   `brew install postgresql@16`).

2. **Provision `DATABASE_URL` for dev and staging.** The pattern is
   `postgresql://postgres:<DB_PASSWORD>@db.<PROJECT_REF>.supabase.co:5432/postgres`.
   Get the password from the Supabase dashboard
   (_Project Settings → Database → Connection string_). Store these
   per-environment; never commit them.

3. **Apply the migrations** (idempotent; safe to re-run):

   ```bash
   # Dev
   DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres:<dev-password>@db.<dev-ref>.supabase.co:5432/postgres" \
     npm run db:migrate

   # Staging
   DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres:<staging-password>@db.<staging-ref>.supabase.co:5432/postgres" \
     npm run db:migrate
   ```

4. **Verify the applied schema:**

   ```bash
   psql "$DATABASE_URL" -v ON_ERROR_STOP=1 -f scripts/db/verify.sql
   ```

   Expected final line:
   `NOTICE:  verify: ok - extensions, enums, tables, RLS, GiST indexes, helpers, storage policies, and core policies are all present.`

5. **Seed the dev database** (refused if `APP_ENV=production`):

   ```bash
   APP_ENV=development \
   DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres:<dev-password>@db.<dev-ref>.supabase.co:5432/postgres" \
     npm run db:seed
   ```

   Optionally seed staging the same way with `APP_ENV=staging`.

6. **Provision a disposable Supabase project for tests** and export:
   ```
   TEST_SUPABASE_URL=https://<ref>.supabase.co
   TEST_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=...
   TEST_SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=...
   ```
   This unblocks `tests/rls/policies.test.ts` (RLS fence verification)
   and `tests/integration/profiles.test.ts` (PostgREST round-trips).
   The QA agent's suite already self-skips when these are absent, so CI
   stays green; once provisioned the suites run unchanged.

7. **Regenerate `lib/types/database.ts`** with
   `npx supabase gen types typescript --project-id <dev-ref>` once the
   migrations land. Replace the hand-authored placeholder; the Phase 0
   shapes are deliberately conservative so the swap is a no-op for
   every consuming agent.

8. **Self-verification fence (CORE PRODUCT RULE #9 — deferred).**
   `companion_profiles_update_self` lets the owner update every column,
   which technically allows a malicious caller (with their own JWT
   against PostgREST) to set
   `verification_status = 'verified' / verified_at = now()`. The
   application surface deliberately offers no such field write, but
   the DB does not block it. The right fix is a `before update` trigger
   on `companion_profiles` that, when
   `auth.role() <> 'service_role'`, rejects writes to
   `verification_status`, `verified_at`, `stripe_connect_account_id`,
   `stripe_payouts_enabled`, `avg_rating`, `rating_count`. Flagged as
   a Database-agent follow-up to be authored alongside the admin
   verification surface (Auth's open item #4 + Trust & Safety phase).

9. **Open product decisions still routed to the Orchestrator** (these
   shape future migrations, not this one):
   - Platform fee % — `payments.platform_fee_cents` is wired; the rule
     is owned by Payments + Orchestrator.
   - Escrow release trigger — column wiring exists; the actual trigger
     (both tap "done"? timer? Core API decision) is unresolved.
   - Cancellation policy — `bookings.cancelled_by`,
     `cancellation_reason`, and `payments.escrow_status='refunded'` are
     wired; refund-tier rules are not.
   - Verification depth — `verification_status` enum is in place; the
     workflow steps belong to Auth & Identity.
   - T&S review of `reviews_select_public` — currently public so
     companion-profile rendering works; T&S may want to gate
     reviews-of-seekers to verified booking partners only. Flagged for
     their Phase 5 audit, not changed unilaterally.
